<h2 class="chapter">4 Limitations</h2>

<p>There are currently some known limitations when using Octave.app. These limitations need not to be reported on an Octave mailing list. But if you find other bugs or other limitations in the Octave.app respectively Octave then please report them to <a href="mailto:bug-octave@octave.org">bug-octave@octave.org</a>.

     <ul>
<li><b>Fortran90 code files cannot be compiled.</b> <br>
Fortran90 and Fortran95 code files etc. cannot be compiled when using the command <span class="command">mkoctfile</span> on the command line or when using the commands <span class="command">mkoctfile</span> or <span class="command">mex</span> in Octave. The reason is that the program <span class="command">f2c</span> has been set up in Octave.app that can just convert Fortran77 code files into C&ndash;files. The C&ndash;files are then compiled with the command <span class="command">gcc</span> that comes with your Apple's XCode Tools (Install these from 'DVD 1 of your Mac OS X Install Discs'). The <span class="command">f2c</span> program is one of the smallest and oldest free Fortran converters/compilers available. Setting up another Fortran compiler that can compile Fortran90 and Fortran95 code files (eg. <span class="command">gfortran</span>) for all the different versions of Apple's XCode Tools and <span class="command">gcc</span> versions is too difficult. We hope that <span class="command">gfortran</span> will become part of Apple's XCode Tools so that we do not need to set up <span class="command">f2c</span> anymore. <br> <br>

<li><b>Some packages from Octave&ndash;Forge's website cannot be installed.</b> <br>
Some of Octave&ndash;Forge's packages cannot be installed because of the reason of a missing <span class="command">gfortran</span> command described before. Known packages that cannot be installed because they come with Fortran90 code files are
          <ul>
<li>optiminterp
</ul>
     If you want to find out more information why the installation of a specific package fails use the command <span class="command">pkg -v &lt;package.tar.gz&gt;</span> that runs the <span class="command">pkg</span> command in verbose mode. <br> <br>

<li><b>No spaces in the pathname before octave.app.</b> <br>
Do not install Octave.app in a place of your filesystem including spaces in the pathname before Octave.app. Valid destinations eg. are <span class="file">/Application/Octave.app</span> or <span class="file">/Users/Me/Desktop/Octave.app</span>. Not valid destinations including spaces in the pathname eg. are <span class="file">/Applications/Other Apps/Desktop/Octave.app</span> and <span class="file">/Users/My Home/Desktop/Octave.app</span>. If you set up Octave.app with a not valid pathname then this might result in different errors at startup or when running the Octave application that cannot be reproduced.

</ul>
   
