<h2 class="chapter">5 FAQs</h2>

<p>
     <ul>
<li><b>Is there a 64&ndash;bit version of Octave.app available?</b> <br>
There is no 64&ndash;bit version of Octave.app available. If you'd like to install a 64&ndash;bit version of Octave then you need to set up one for your own. A good starting point for creating such a binary would be <a href="http://wiki.octave.org/wiki.pl?OctaveForMac">http://wiki.octave.org/wiki.pl?OctaveForMac</a>.  Please consider contributing regular builds to octave-forge. <br> <br>

<li><b>How can I startup Octave.app?</b> <br>
After Octave.app has been placed to your desktop or to your applications folder or anywhere else in your filesystem tree you can double&ndash;click the Octave.app icon. This opens a new Terminal.app window and starts Octave in this new Terminal.app. Another way to open the Octave.app is to use the command <span class="command">open</span> on the command line. If you installed Octave.app in your applications folder then a one time startup might look like eg.
     <pre class="example">          bash ~$ open /Applications/Octave.app
     </pre>
     <p>
<li><b>How can I startup Octave.app with a XTerm window?</b> <br>
If you prefer using the application <span class="command">xterm</span> instead of the Terminal.app that comes with your X11 runtime environment (Install from 'DVD 1 of your Mac OS X Install Discs') then you can set up the environment variable <var>OCTAVE_TERMINAL=X11</var> before starting the Octave.app. A description about how to set up environment variables for all processes launched by a specific user can be found at <a href="http://developer.apple.com/qa/qa2001/qa1067.html">http://developer.apple.com/qa/qa2001/qa1067.html</a>. If you installed Octave.app in your applications folder then a one time startup might look like eg.
     <pre class="example">          bash ~$ export OCTAVE_TERMINAL=X11
          bash ~$ open /Applications/Octave.app
     </pre>
     <p>
<li><b>How can I startup Octave in a Terminal.app or an XTerm that is already running?</b> <br>
A modified startup script has been placed into the Octave.app that can be used to startup Octave in an already running Terminal.app or a <span class="command">xterm</span> application. The place of this startup script is <code>&lt;octave.app&gt;/Contents/Resources/bin/octave</code>. If you have installed Octave.app in your applications folder then a startup in your already running Terminal.app or XTerm application might look like eg.
     <pre class="example">          bash ~$ /Applications/Octave.app/Contents/Resources/bin/octave
     </pre>
     <p>Another way to use Octave from the command line is to set up a link to the Octave startup script of Octave.app that is placed somewhere in your system's <var>PATH</var>. If you have installed Octave.app in your applications folder then setting up a link and starting up Octave might look like eg.
     <pre class="example">          bash ~$ sudo ln -s /usr/bin/octave /Applications/Octave.app/Contents/Resources/bin/octave
          bash ~$ octave
     </pre>
     <p>
<li><b>How can I use mkoctfile in a Terminal.app or a XTerm that is already running?</b> <br>
A modified startup script has been placed into the Octave.app that can be used to run mkoctfile in an already running Terminal.app or a <span class="command">xterm</span> application. The place of this startup script is <code>&lt;octave.app&gt;/Contents/Resources/bin/mkoctfile</code>. If you have installed Octave.app in your applications folder then the use of the command <span class="command">mkoctfile</span> might look like eg.
     <pre class="example">          bash ~$ /Applications/Octave.app/Contents/Resources/bin/mkoctfile &lt;file.cc&gt;
     </pre>
     <p>Another way to use the command <span class="command">mkoctfile</span> from the command line is to set up a link to the <span class="command">mkoctfile</span> startup script of Octave.app that is placed somewhere in your system's <var>PATH</var>. If you have installed Octave.app in your applications folder then setting up a link and starting up Octave might look like eg.
     <pre class="example">          bash ~$ sudo ln -s /usr/bin/mkoctfile /Applications/Octave.app/Contents/Resources/bin/mkoctfile
          bash ~$ mkoctfile &lt;file.cc&gt;
     </pre>
     <p>
</ul>
   
